data.content:
All three code snippets hit EF Core 10 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` ŌĆö no longer accepts `Expression<Func<...>>`

The setter parameter changed from an expression tree to a plain `Func<...>`. Your manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` code **won't compile**. Replace it with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more expression-tree plumbing needed.

---

### 2. Complex type columns ŌĆö two changes

**a) Shared column names are now uniquified.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously mapped to the same `Street` column silently (data corruption risk). Now EF appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). If you have an existing DB and want to keep the old names, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types use the full path in column names.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; now it becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Tip:** If you're creating a new DB, the new defaults are better ŌĆö just generate a fresh migration. Only pin names if you need to match an existing schema.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` ŌĆö new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ŌåÉ new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
